00:00:46.680 --> 00:00:56.230
The first is an example
from Philippe Boudon's book,

00:00:56.230 --> 00:00:58.500
Lived-in Architecture.

00:00:58.500 --> 00:01:02.490
This is his housing for
steel workers at Pessac,

00:01:02.490 --> 00:01:12.720
near Bordeaux, which Boudon
studied after a period of time

00:01:12.720 --> 00:01:17.280
and made these
drawings of the changes

00:01:17.280 --> 00:01:22.380
that people have made to
the original plan, which

00:01:22.380 --> 00:01:23.370
is the top left.

00:01:26.110 --> 00:01:32.660
The elevations indicate
a couple of things,

00:01:32.660 --> 00:01:35.925
because I'm not going to go into
any detail about this example.

00:01:38.940 --> 00:01:46.470
People enclosed the open porch
of Corbusier's to make garages.

00:01:46.470 --> 00:01:49.940
They replaced long,
linear windows

00:01:49.940 --> 00:01:56.360
by rectangular windows of
a much more oblong nature,

00:01:56.360 --> 00:02:03.080
arguing that Corbusier's
windows were not modern enough

00:02:03.080 --> 00:02:05.590
and so on and so on.

00:02:05.590 --> 00:02:11.140
When Corbusier was asked by
Boudon about these changes,

00:02:11.140 --> 00:02:19.050
he said, to be grammatically
as possible, life

00:02:19.050 --> 00:02:20.610
is more important than art.

00:02:27.400 --> 00:02:32.200
There was no indication that
he expected or made provisions

00:02:32.200 --> 00:02:36.140
for changes to take place.

00:02:36.140 --> 00:02:41.740
He was central to
modernism, that time

00:02:41.740 --> 00:02:46.870
was captured within the
space of the project.

00:02:46.870 --> 00:02:52.480
He neither looked forward to
changes that could be made

00:02:52.480 --> 00:02:56.350
nor did he look back to
the possibility of history

00:02:56.350 --> 00:03:00.890
or memory affecting your work.

00:03:00.890 --> 00:03:06.280
So one ism, as I tried
to indicate on Tuesday,

00:03:06.280 --> 00:03:12.350
was the notion of
fixed culture, which

00:03:12.350 --> 00:03:18.520
operated with the production of
objects which had no reference

00:03:18.520 --> 00:03:21.820
backwards of any value.

00:03:21.820 --> 00:03:26.230
Corbusier is a classic
example of a man who

00:03:26.230 --> 00:03:36.730
denies the 19th century street
forever and then proceeded

00:03:36.730 --> 00:03:42.900
to make projects like this
one, in which the steel

00:03:42.900 --> 00:03:47.880
workers themselves find
the capacity to change

00:03:47.880 --> 00:03:51.630
without the change
being premeditated.

00:03:51.630 --> 00:03:58.020
We're going to be looking today
at the issue of looking forward

00:03:58.020 --> 00:04:02.730
and what unpredictability means.

