00:07:09.730 --> 00:07:16.090
Reaction after
the end of CIM was

00:07:16.090 --> 00:07:18.760
in the hands of a small
group of architects

00:07:18.760 --> 00:07:25.840
called Team 10, who put forward
the possibility that time

00:07:25.840 --> 00:07:29.590
could be escaped from.

00:07:29.590 --> 00:07:30.820
That's my words.

00:07:30.820 --> 00:07:32.780
They didn't write it.

00:07:32.780 --> 00:07:36.190
Alison and Peter Smithson,
Team 10 primaries,

00:07:36.190 --> 00:07:43.930
the doctrine of their
work and theories,

00:07:43.930 --> 00:07:52.110
they were interested in
notions of unpredictability,

00:07:52.110 --> 00:07:54.560
circumstance, probability.

00:07:59.210 --> 00:08:04.160
They were interested in
the notion of the temporary

00:08:04.160 --> 00:08:07.190
and the ephemeral
versus the permanent.

00:08:15.730 --> 00:08:18.280
Secondly, they were
interested in the flow,

00:08:18.280 --> 00:08:25.390
in the idea that movement
systems, particularly

00:08:25.390 --> 00:08:28.780
those that create
interaction and connection

00:08:28.780 --> 00:08:33.309
were fundamental to their work.

00:08:33.309 --> 00:08:44.020
And thirdly, they tried to
argue for social reality, which

00:08:44.020 --> 00:08:50.080
involved the
complexity of occasion,

00:08:50.080 --> 00:08:56.060
as it occurred in most
situations at the time.

00:08:56.060 --> 00:08:59.830
They invented words,
like most architects do.

00:08:59.830 --> 00:09:04.750
Socioplastics is
their invention.

00:09:04.750 --> 00:09:09.160
Socioplastics use
that word which

00:09:09.160 --> 00:09:14.260
embraces what the painters like
Richard Hamilton and Eduardo

00:09:14.260 --> 00:09:19.060
Paolozzi were trying to
do in their painting.

00:09:19.060 --> 00:09:21.400
It's interesting
how few architects

00:09:21.400 --> 00:09:24.520
of the modern movement or
the post-modern movement

00:09:24.520 --> 00:09:27.850
have had much association
with painting.

00:09:27.850 --> 00:09:31.130
Frank Gehry is,
perhaps, the only one.

00:09:31.130 --> 00:09:36.100
Steven Holl, to some extent,
connect the interpretation

00:09:36.100 --> 00:09:42.880
of architecture in light to
certain ideas about painting,

00:09:42.880 --> 00:09:48.620
whereas the Modernists were
very much in the mood of all

00:09:48.620 --> 00:09:54.220
the painting revolutions,
which occurred largely

00:09:54.220 --> 00:09:56.315
in Paris and in Europe.

00:09:59.960 --> 00:10:12.600
So we have the notion of
change, the notion of flow,

00:10:12.600 --> 00:10:18.450
and the notion of socioplastics
as central to Team 10's work.

00:10:18.450 --> 00:10:20.910
We will look a little
bit at Team 10's work.

00:10:20.910 --> 00:10:24.630
But I haven't got the
time in this class

00:10:24.630 --> 00:10:29.370
to deliberate fully on Team
10 and their architecture

00:10:29.370 --> 00:10:30.885
and their urbanistic work.

00:10:35.150 --> 00:10:38.045
We have to accept that you
cannot predict the future.

00:10:42.160 --> 00:10:45.760
There's a book by Paul
Ormerod, an Englishman,

00:10:45.760 --> 00:10:51.710
called Why Most Things
Fail, which sets out

00:10:51.710 --> 00:10:57.890
that we maintain to achieve
a particular outcome

00:10:57.890 --> 00:11:01.100
but the complexity of the
world, even in apparently

00:11:01.100 --> 00:11:04.400
simple situations,
appears to be so great

00:11:04.400 --> 00:11:08.220
that it's not within our
power to ordain the future.

