00:13:54.250 --> 00:14:00.640
Let's just list, if we can,
some of the conventional methods

00:14:00.640 --> 00:14:04.720
of achieving
flexibility in cities.

00:14:04.720 --> 00:14:12.890
Number one, land banking,
you can endow land

00:14:12.890 --> 00:14:18.730
with cheap uses, farming,
parking lots, and so on,

00:14:18.730 --> 00:14:23.390
on the grounds that, in future
when land becomes more scarce,

00:14:23.390 --> 00:14:29.060
they will be able to be reused
without much demolition.

00:14:29.060 --> 00:14:33.530
Farming is not an option which
has been used in urbanism very

00:14:33.530 --> 00:14:37.270
much if at all.

00:14:37.270 --> 00:14:43.300
Farming in New York is on
terraces and high 100-feet

00:14:43.300 --> 00:14:46.790
above the ground, or 1,000
feet above the ground.

00:14:50.680 --> 00:14:56.070
Secondly, easements--
easements are

00:14:56.070 --> 00:15:07.890
rights of way which can be
endowed with limited use,

00:15:07.890 --> 00:15:11.880
such as on the
sides of highways.

00:15:11.880 --> 00:15:13.950
When we spoke
about Robert Moses,

00:15:13.950 --> 00:15:21.150
I spoke about the lack of
his provision of easements

00:15:21.150 --> 00:15:23.250
on his freeways.

00:15:23.250 --> 00:15:27.180
The cost of providing
the easement

00:15:27.180 --> 00:15:32.880
would have allowed the addition
of public transportation

00:15:32.880 --> 00:15:36.990
next to these roads at
a cost, which is now

00:15:36.990 --> 00:15:39.450
estimated to be a
fraction of what it now

00:15:39.450 --> 00:15:42.000
would cost to do them.

00:15:42.000 --> 00:15:52.780
So you allow the possibility
of an event taking place

00:15:52.780 --> 00:15:57.670
on land which is easily
available and costs very little

00:15:57.670 --> 00:16:01.255
initially, but increases
in value as time passes.

00:16:04.340 --> 00:16:06.590
The problem with
prediction is that there's

00:16:06.590 --> 00:16:09.440
a difference between
the right prediction

00:16:09.440 --> 00:16:11.930
and the excessive prediction.

00:16:11.930 --> 00:16:19.250
Now, it's between too little
response and too much response.

00:16:19.250 --> 00:16:29.020
Prediction costs money
under most circumstances.

00:16:29.020 --> 00:16:33.010
You can also do
excessive prediction.

00:16:33.010 --> 00:16:36.430
I think I showed you a diagram
of a South African mining

00:16:36.430 --> 00:16:40.420
town, a classic case
where the town was

00:16:40.420 --> 00:16:45.820
designed so that the central
businesses could expand.

00:16:45.820 --> 00:16:49.240
The expansion area around
the center of the city

00:16:49.240 --> 00:16:54.700
was so poorly treated, so badly
landscaped, not landscaped

00:16:54.700 --> 00:16:55.860
at all.

00:16:55.860 --> 00:16:58.150
It was just dirt.

00:16:58.150 --> 00:17:00.460
It, in fact, caused the
center business area

00:17:00.460 --> 00:17:07.630
not only to grow, but to decline
in size instead of to expand.

00:17:07.630 --> 00:17:14.260
Leaving land for expansion
is one of the ideas

00:17:14.260 --> 00:17:16.240
that we'll look at a
bit more carefully.

00:17:23.950 --> 00:17:28.650
You can leave open
space for consumption,

00:17:28.650 --> 00:17:33.360
assuming a coarse
grain in your town.

00:17:33.360 --> 00:17:39.730
I will show you the example of
the Seoul the Olympics in 1988,

00:17:39.730 --> 00:17:45.270
which built its Olympic Games
on the basis of a fairly

00:17:45.270 --> 00:17:48.850
large open space system.

00:17:48.850 --> 00:17:53.100
Who knows the 1988
Olympic Games?

00:17:53.100 --> 00:17:54.240
Were you there?

00:17:54.240 --> 00:17:56.250
AUDIENCE: Not at the
Games, I know the site.

00:17:56.250 --> 00:17:57.667
JULIAN BEINART:
You know the site.

00:17:57.667 --> 00:17:58.620
Yeah.

00:17:58.620 --> 00:17:59.820
Yeah.

00:17:59.820 --> 00:18:06.660
It's a classic example of the
cannibalization of easy access

00:18:06.660 --> 00:18:07.830
space.

00:18:07.830 --> 00:18:09.880
Open space is easy access.

00:18:09.880 --> 00:18:13.200
It's cheap-- not cheap
in the public's mind,

00:18:13.200 --> 00:18:18.030
but cheap in the
promoter's mind.

00:18:18.030 --> 00:18:21.750
And most of the facilities,
including the Olympic Village

00:18:21.750 --> 00:18:26.430
by Kyu Sung Woo, who
lives here in Cambridge,

00:18:26.430 --> 00:18:29.310
was built on this
available land.

00:18:29.310 --> 00:18:33.600
We'll come to
Seoul '88 later on.

00:18:33.600 --> 00:18:35.500
I'm just running
through some of these.

00:18:39.180 --> 00:18:45.390
There's infrastructure
for flexibility.

00:18:45.390 --> 00:18:49.200
When we designed the MIT
Brain and Cognitive Sciences

00:18:49.200 --> 00:18:53.280
building, we had to allow
for the C86 railroad

00:18:53.280 --> 00:18:57.030
to run through underneath
the building that

00:18:57.030 --> 00:19:01.710
made an extraordinary difference
in the kind of building

00:19:01.710 --> 00:19:03.690
which you could design

00:19:03.690 --> 00:19:11.100
but we calculated that if
the air Rights Committee

00:19:11.100 --> 00:19:15.030
owned the air right
over the C86 railroad,

00:19:15.030 --> 00:19:19.020
about 22 feet or 15 meters.

00:19:19.020 --> 00:19:20.010
I'm not sure which.

00:19:20.010 --> 00:19:22.340
I think it's 22 feet.

00:19:22.340 --> 00:19:27.330
MIT can build 22 feet above
the plane of the railroad.

00:19:27.330 --> 00:19:29.735
We calculated when
working on this that,

00:19:29.735 --> 00:19:36.630
if MIT exercised this option and
built on the maximum air rights

00:19:36.630 --> 00:19:37.500
that the--

00:19:37.500 --> 00:19:40.950
well, they have the air rights.

00:19:40.950 --> 00:19:43.880
The degree to which they
can build vertically

00:19:43.880 --> 00:19:46.680
will have to be
sanctioned by the city.

00:19:46.680 --> 00:19:50.400
But we calculated
that, if MIT wished

00:19:50.400 --> 00:19:57.570
to expand its campus
vertically over the air rights,

00:19:57.570 --> 00:20:01.980
the development would be
worth billions of dollars

00:20:01.980 --> 00:20:05.985
in Cambridge in terms
of square footage.

00:20:05.985 --> 00:20:11.220
So imagine the possibility of
a future in which MIT could

00:20:11.220 --> 00:20:15.210
build above a railway line.

00:20:19.240 --> 00:20:22.850
The fact is that we
only built to the height

00:20:22.850 --> 00:20:26.450
that Cambridge allows in
our building, which was

00:20:26.450 --> 00:20:28.190
large enough for our program.

00:20:31.050 --> 00:20:37.770
But this friction caused
by a movement system.

00:20:37.770 --> 00:20:40.320
Corbusier's
proposition of building

00:20:40.320 --> 00:20:46.320
under the freeways in Algiers
is not feasible anymore.

00:20:46.320 --> 00:20:49.470
The noise and pollution
caused by the automobiles

00:20:49.470 --> 00:20:53.160
would make it
virtually impossible

00:20:53.160 --> 00:20:56.700
to build under the freeways.

00:20:56.700 --> 00:21:02.040
One of the dramatic futures
in the next 50 years

00:21:02.040 --> 00:21:05.010
is going to be to how
to capture the space

00:21:05.010 --> 00:21:08.820
under elevated freeways
all over the world.

00:21:08.820 --> 00:21:15.120
They're elevated to
a considerable height

00:21:15.120 --> 00:21:16.920
because you have to be
able to pass through

00:21:16.920 --> 00:21:22.500
with a truck, which means
that you have to have ramps

00:21:22.500 --> 00:21:25.920
at 1 in 10 or 1 in 5.

00:21:25.920 --> 00:21:28.050
Depending on how
steep you are, you

00:21:28.050 --> 00:21:31.540
can take a large
amount of space.

00:21:31.540 --> 00:21:38.430
So I haven't seen a
proposition in recent times

00:21:38.430 --> 00:21:42.420
anywhere in the world
for capturing the space

00:21:42.420 --> 00:21:48.340
under a freeway in
a positive sense.

00:21:48.340 --> 00:21:52.740
We have one SMR
student project thesis,

00:21:52.740 --> 00:21:55.680
which you'll see in
three weeks time,

00:21:55.680 --> 00:22:00.210
which tries to do this in
Boston with great difficulty.

