above a plane,
which for the moment

00:22:11.410 --> 00:22:15.370
is used by a railroad or
freeway, and the development

00:22:15.370 --> 00:22:22.770
below that plane even
penetrating into the ground

00:22:22.770 --> 00:22:26.770
are options which
utopianists have examined

00:22:26.770 --> 00:22:30.370
and wondered about.

00:22:30.370 --> 00:22:32.155
So we have to include
them on our list.

00:22:36.670 --> 00:22:39.910
Lastly, is the
question of geometry.

00:22:39.910 --> 00:22:42.550
And most of the
rest of my talk is

00:22:42.550 --> 00:22:47.320
going to deal with people who
have used the idea of geometry

00:22:47.320 --> 00:22:49.855
to allow for future change.

00:22:53.640 --> 00:22:56.340
OK.

00:22:56.340 --> 00:23:01.605
One of the people who argued
for the impact of geometry

00:23:01.605 --> 00:23:03.785
is [? Maria Zepharado's ?]
thesis.

00:23:06.540 --> 00:23:11.280
Maria was in this class
and became interested

00:23:11.280 --> 00:23:14.160
in the idea of change.

00:23:14.160 --> 00:23:21.660
She wanted to study a city
and make some speculation

00:23:21.660 --> 00:23:27.075
about how urban
transformation took place.

00:23:31.420 --> 00:23:39.700
She decided after being
forced to limit her thesis

00:23:39.700 --> 00:23:41.365
to take a MIT.

00:23:44.800 --> 00:23:49.930
MIT, Shadrach Woods, the
architect of the firm, Josic--

00:23:54.770 --> 00:23:58.220
oh, I forget the name
of the French firm,

00:23:58.220 --> 00:24:03.380
was an American architect
who developed the word ground

00:24:03.380 --> 00:24:06.760
scraper as a model
of MIT and used

00:24:06.760 --> 00:24:11.445
as the basis for the design
of the Free University campus

00:24:11.445 --> 00:24:11.945
in Berlin.

00:24:15.750 --> 00:24:22.650
Maria worked with the
drawings in the MIT archives,

00:24:22.650 --> 00:24:25.920
which had never been
looked at before,

00:24:25.920 --> 00:24:28.590
and made an assessment
of the number

00:24:28.590 --> 00:24:33.330
of geometric configurations
that allowed the campus

00:24:33.330 --> 00:24:36.750
to grow in the way that it did.

00:24:36.750 --> 00:24:40.515
I haven't got time to go
into this detail, as always.

00:24:43.500 --> 00:24:44.970
Why are we so short of time?

00:24:47.500 --> 00:24:49.830
Is it because we
try to do too much?

00:24:52.370 --> 00:24:55.675
But if you don't do too much,
who says what is enough?

00:24:59.580 --> 00:25:02.700
Should one take one
project like this

00:25:02.700 --> 00:25:07.920
and spend a semester
studying it in detail?

00:25:07.920 --> 00:25:11.310
Would you gain more
from doing that

00:25:11.310 --> 00:25:15.180
versus attending a class which
tries to cover everything

00:25:15.180 --> 00:25:16.305
in the world?

00:25:16.305 --> 00:25:17.275
[LAUGHTER]

00:25:20.185 --> 00:25:23.100
Well, you made your choice.

00:25:28.680 --> 00:25:33.810
Among our findings,
six stand out,

00:25:33.810 --> 00:25:39.030
the existence of an
underlying circulation system.

00:25:39.030 --> 00:25:46.590
MIT has a block size
of 65 feet in width

00:25:46.590 --> 00:25:49.380
in the central corridor
most of the time.

00:25:52.820 --> 00:25:56.310
There are three
kinds of stems used.

00:25:56.310 --> 00:25:58.760
Number three, the quality
of the knuckles-- whenever

00:25:58.760 --> 00:26:01.890
a building changed directions.

00:26:01.890 --> 00:26:06.500
Almost always when
there's an opportunity

00:26:06.500 --> 00:26:11.090
to change direction, the
vertical circulation system

00:26:11.090 --> 00:26:21.610
of elevators and staircases
are contained in the knuckle.

00:26:21.610 --> 00:26:23.920
So she shows that
every time a building

00:26:23.920 --> 00:26:28.330
changes direction
it is free of having

00:26:28.330 --> 00:26:33.700
to replace the vertical
circulation system.

00:26:37.000 --> 00:26:39.100
It means that the
circulation system

00:26:39.100 --> 00:26:42.400
becomes more intense as it
is joined to other systems.

00:26:45.260 --> 00:26:48.160
The fully equipped
unit section--

00:26:48.160 --> 00:26:51.610
from the [INAUDIBLE] system.

00:26:51.610 --> 00:26:55.550
The courtyard is future space.

00:26:55.550 --> 00:27:01.030
I never realized that MIT
intended the courtyard system

00:27:01.030 --> 00:27:04.480
as an opportunity for
building expansion.

00:27:04.480 --> 00:27:05.790
Thank god they haven't.

00:27:09.250 --> 00:27:15.220
The facades-- where facades
were considered to be permanent,

00:27:15.220 --> 00:27:17.890
they were built of
granite or limestone.

00:27:17.890 --> 00:27:22.150
Where the facades were
considered to be temporary,

00:27:22.150 --> 00:27:24.760
they were built of brick,
yellow brick facade.

00:27:27.820 --> 00:27:35.500
So she argues very
systematically with a lot

00:27:35.500 --> 00:27:44.560
of data that there was a
kind of DNA in the system not

00:27:44.560 --> 00:27:48.970
a very profound DNA, but
a very simple DNA, which

00:27:48.970 --> 00:28:00.230
allowed MIT to grow until
2004 on its own land.

00:28:00.230 --> 00:28:03.350
Our building, the Brain
and Cognitive Center,

00:28:03.350 --> 00:28:06.330
is on the other side
of Vassar Street.

00:28:06.330 --> 00:28:10.490
It was the first
time a building--

00:28:10.490 --> 00:28:14.240
not the first time, but
one of the first times

00:28:14.240 --> 00:28:19.460
the major building was built
outside of the limited campus.

00:28:19.460 --> 00:28:27.470
We proposed an aerial connection
from building whatever-it-is

00:28:27.470 --> 00:28:34.860
across Vassar Street to a
place on the second floor

00:28:34.860 --> 00:28:37.100
of the Brain and
Cognitive Center.

00:28:37.100 --> 00:28:40.070
MIT wouldn't build it.

00:28:40.070 --> 00:28:42.590
We tried very hard
to get it built.

00:28:42.590 --> 00:28:46.160
In fact, the German
engineer [? George Sly ?]

00:28:46.160 --> 00:28:52.130
who worked on the
Freedom Tower in New York

00:28:52.130 --> 00:28:56.287
is probably the best structural
engineer in the world, designed

00:28:56.287 --> 00:28:56.870
the connector.

00:28:56.870 --> 00:29:00.800
But MIT didn't.

00:29:00.800 --> 00:29:03.870
MIT now faces an
expansion possibility

00:29:03.870 --> 00:29:09.470
which is not as simple as
expanding on your own land.

00:29:09.470 --> 00:29:12.860
It has to deal with urban
infrastructure of much more

00:29:12.860 --> 00:29:13.730
complex nature.

00:29:19.430 --> 00:29:24.610
Another use of geometry,
which we mentioned before

00:29:24.610 --> 00:29:31.140
is in the Llewelyn-Davies plan
for Milton Keynes in London one

00:29:31.140 --> 00:29:36.250
of the Mark 3 New Towns.

00:29:36.250 --> 00:29:40.610
You'll remember that
the grid is used.

00:29:40.610 --> 00:29:44.830
And the grid is spaced at
1 kilometer by 1 kilometer,

00:29:44.830 --> 00:29:51.670
not 1 mile by 1 mile,
so that the consequence

00:29:51.670 --> 00:29:57.730
of the generation of volume
within this enclosed grid space

00:29:57.730 --> 00:30:00.670
would not be too
large and require

00:30:00.670 --> 00:30:03.266
great separated interaction.

00:30:06.640 --> 00:30:11.520
Some other ideas--
the whole premise

00:30:11.520 --> 00:30:16.980
of Milton Keynes' his plan
he summarized as follows.

00:30:16.980 --> 00:30:19.440
"The central aim of
the plan is to arrange

00:30:19.440 --> 00:30:23.640
the necessary fixed
elements, transport drainage

00:30:23.640 --> 00:30:27.000
water supply in
a new city, so as

00:30:27.000 --> 00:30:30.705
to allow the greatest possible
scope for freedom and change.

00:30:36.630 --> 00:30:39.180
It has been planned
as far as possible

00:30:39.180 --> 00:30:42.510
to allow wide varieties
in patterns of life

00:30:42.510 --> 00:30:47.400
and the greatest possible
choice for the future."

00:30:47.400 --> 00:30:51.780
There are two things in
the geometry of the--

00:30:51.780 --> 00:30:56.790
well, in the application
of the geometry.

00:30:56.790 --> 00:31:00.540
Number one is the
idea, as I drew

00:31:00.540 --> 00:31:03.480
on the blackboard, of
recognizing the possibility

00:31:03.480 --> 00:31:05.820
of a space frame system.

00:31:05.820 --> 00:31:08.790
A space frame system
in architecture

00:31:08.790 --> 00:31:14.400
is a system which spans distance
and allows you to put points

00:31:14.400 --> 00:31:18.870
on the load system at
any point as opposed

00:31:18.870 --> 00:31:22.740
to point and beam system,
where you can only

00:31:22.740 --> 00:31:29.320
load the system where there is
a column beneath your point.

00:31:29.320 --> 00:31:33.960
So it's kind of pointless
system or freedom of pointing,

00:31:33.960 --> 00:31:38.010
which allows almost any
kind of change to exist.

00:31:38.010 --> 00:31:42.150
The notion of deciding what
the maximum amount that you

00:31:42.150 --> 00:31:48.210
can allow before the system
cripples itself is interesting.

00:31:48.210 --> 00:31:54.840
You have to use mathematical
prediction systems

00:31:54.840 --> 00:31:57.000
like the Poisson distribution.

00:31:57.000 --> 00:31:59.490
Who knows what the
Poisson distribution is?

00:32:02.190 --> 00:32:03.120
You should know.

00:32:05.810 --> 00:32:07.520
If you're going to
design a university

00:32:07.520 --> 00:32:11.600
campus or a
schoolroom, how do you

00:32:11.600 --> 00:32:17.000
decide on the distribution
of the sizes of classrooms?

00:32:20.630 --> 00:32:22.520
You're architects.

00:32:22.520 --> 00:32:25.910
You're in advanced
standing at MIT.

00:32:25.910 --> 00:32:27.230
You're doing doctorates.

00:32:27.230 --> 00:32:30.450
You're doing all kinds
of advanced degrees.

00:32:30.450 --> 00:32:32.630
And if I ask you the
simple proposition

00:32:32.630 --> 00:32:34.640
that, if you had
to walk out of here

00:32:34.640 --> 00:32:39.440
and you were in Burma
somewhere and they decided

00:32:39.440 --> 00:32:45.410
to build a new university, how
would you decide on its program

00:32:45.410 --> 00:32:47.620
without knowing the
Poisson distribution?

00:32:50.420 --> 00:32:53.630
The Department of Mathematics
at Cambridge University,

00:32:53.630 --> 00:32:56.660
a new building, is
designed on the basis

00:32:56.660 --> 00:32:59.780
of Poisson distribution.

00:32:59.780 --> 00:33:02.480
It allocates
probability of sizes

00:33:02.480 --> 00:33:05.720
given certain average rates.

00:33:05.720 --> 00:33:08.390
I'm not trying to be clever.

00:33:08.390 --> 00:33:11.960
I'm just trying
to say that there

00:33:11.960 --> 00:33:16.850
are statistical measures
which give one a better

00:33:16.850 --> 00:33:18.455
prediction about the future.

00:33:21.430 --> 00:33:24.540
One of the best subjects I
ever studied in graduate school

00:33:24.540 --> 00:33:25.800
was statistics.

00:33:25.800 --> 00:33:31.350
I hated it, but it made me
aware of the fact that you

00:33:31.350 --> 00:33:34.200
can generate knowledge
through sampling

00:33:34.200 --> 00:33:36.930
systems of great capacity.

00:33:39.450 --> 00:33:42.990
I was staggered when
my professor said,

00:33:42.990 --> 00:33:46.080
the only reason we
have live matches

00:33:46.080 --> 00:33:52.290
is because we know statistically
how many matches fail.

00:33:52.290 --> 00:33:56.310
And we can predict the
production of boxes of matches

00:33:56.310 --> 00:34:02.460
without any of them
failing or 99% succeeding--

00:34:02.460 --> 00:34:08.010
staggering, but a
simple observation.

00:34:08.010 --> 00:34:14.170
The Poisson distribution is
one of the features of a--

00:34:16.969 --> 00:34:21.020
so the second feature
Milton Keynes,

00:34:21.020 --> 00:34:26.000
in trying to predict
the possibility of,

00:34:26.000 --> 00:34:30.290
first of all, diversity
and, secondly, of change

00:34:30.290 --> 00:34:34.010
is to introduce
zoning systems based

00:34:34.010 --> 00:34:35.719
on performance dimensions.

00:34:38.270 --> 00:34:42.679
The reason why German
zoning started out

00:34:42.679 --> 00:34:44.929
was because of the
industrial city

00:34:44.929 --> 00:34:49.880
causing noise and dirt and
fumes and traffic as opposed

00:34:49.880 --> 00:34:54.889
to the quiet notions that are
required in a residential area.

00:34:54.889 --> 00:35:00.560
If today a high tech
company produces

00:35:00.560 --> 00:35:06.080
no noise, no smoke,
no sound, can it not

00:35:06.080 --> 00:35:08.540
be adjacent to a
residential building?

00:35:15.370 --> 00:35:19.990
Of course, I don't know how this
has worked in Milton Keynes.

00:35:19.990 --> 00:35:24.160
If I buy a piece of land and
I make a wonderful garden

00:35:24.160 --> 00:35:27.520
next to it, it has value.

00:35:27.520 --> 00:35:32.230
If the city decides to
build a factory next to it,

00:35:32.230 --> 00:35:35.050
I lose value.

00:35:35.050 --> 00:35:37.810
How do you account
for that change?

00:35:37.810 --> 00:35:40.450
Do you repay me?

00:35:40.450 --> 00:35:44.020
I take you to court
and say I have rights.

00:35:44.020 --> 00:35:49.150
They say, you don't have rights
to predict, to confiscate,

00:35:49.150 --> 00:35:55.370
the rights of development
and so around you.

00:35:55.370 --> 00:35:56.770
It's a fundamental problem.

00:35:56.770 --> 00:36:00.700
If you wish to
design for diversity,

00:36:00.700 --> 00:36:05.050
you can, of course, write a rule
saying that a factory will not

00:36:05.050 --> 00:36:08.500
be within 100 feet.

00:36:08.500 --> 00:36:13.180
But performance dimensions
measure sound, noise,

00:36:13.180 --> 00:36:15.850
frequency of traffic.

00:36:15.850 --> 00:36:20.260
If trucks start working, as they
do in New York, at 5 o'clock

00:36:20.260 --> 00:36:23.690
in the morning and
I want to sleep,

00:36:23.690 --> 00:36:27.940
what right do I have to stop
the trucks from off-loading

00:36:27.940 --> 00:36:29.390
at 5 o'clock in the morning?

00:36:31.960 --> 00:36:34.240
These are tough questions.

00:36:34.240 --> 00:36:40.390
And flexibility simply runs up
against some of these questions

00:36:40.390 --> 00:36:43.260
in a very real sense.

00:36:43.260 --> 00:36:44.980
It will be
interesting to check--

00:36:44.980 --> 00:36:48.730
I need to talk to
John de Monchaux who

00:36:48.730 --> 00:36:51.460
is one of the designers
of Milton Keynes,

00:36:51.460 --> 00:36:53.065
about how this has been handled.

00:36:56.860 --> 00:37:02.680
Rodrigo PÃ©rez de Arce, who
argues in favor of keeping

00:37:02.680 --> 00:37:07.670
existing stock and building
an architecture of addition,

00:37:07.670 --> 00:37:11.590
he says, urbanistically,
it has three advantages.

00:37:16.810 --> 00:37:21.670
"By being a gradual organized
incorporation of parity

00:37:21.670 --> 00:37:25.420
into an existing core,
it implies the use

00:37:25.420 --> 00:37:27.730
of a pre-existing structure.

00:37:27.730 --> 00:37:29.950
And by doing so, it
extends the likelihood

00:37:29.950 --> 00:37:32.285
that it's being useful
for a long time.

00:37:35.780 --> 00:37:42.100
Secondly, it allows for a form
of development characterized

00:37:42.100 --> 00:37:46.660
by its low cost in both
social and material terms."

00:37:46.660 --> 00:37:48.910
I'm not sure that he's right.

00:37:48.910 --> 00:37:55.430
Maybe it's true in Colombia, but
the cost of renewing buildings,

00:37:55.430 --> 00:37:58.700
such as the buildings
around here,

00:37:58.700 --> 00:38:03.100
which have been renewed for
high technology purposes,

00:38:03.100 --> 00:38:06.340
is extensive.

00:38:06.340 --> 00:38:11.710
It's not automatic that, if you
extend a building, all you do

00:38:11.710 --> 00:38:17.020
is put a bedroom, an
addition to a house.

00:38:20.290 --> 00:38:27.730
And thirdly, he says
that this process,

00:38:27.730 --> 00:38:32.890
"this additive transformation
ensures a sense of continuity

00:38:32.890 --> 00:38:36.100
in the construction of
the town and a sense

00:38:36.100 --> 00:38:39.020
of place in both historical
and spatial terms."

00:38:42.090 --> 00:38:44.080
He goes on and on.

00:38:44.080 --> 00:38:48.960
This is the piece from
Architectural Design

00:38:48.960 --> 00:38:52.650
if you can't find the
AA, the little book.

00:38:55.560 --> 00:38:56.480
Let's look.

00:38:56.480 --> 00:39:03.260
And I need you to look
at your transcript.

00:39:03.260 --> 00:39:09.740
Let's look at the development
of a systematic campus

00:39:09.740 --> 00:39:12.365
plan starting in--

00:39:16.180 --> 00:39:18.040
the British were
very intelligent

00:39:18.040 --> 00:39:24.370
after they won the
war, the '39, '45 war.

00:39:24.370 --> 00:39:26.770
They decided under
the Labor government,

00:39:26.770 --> 00:39:31.720
which replaced Churchill--

00:39:31.720 --> 00:39:35.230
Churchill was interestingly
successful as a war leader,

00:39:35.230 --> 00:39:39.895
but helpless as a peace leader.

00:39:42.820 --> 00:39:44.560
Maggie Thatcher was
equally hopeless.

00:39:48.090 --> 00:39:52.620
She was a big war success
with the Falkland Islands,

00:39:52.620 --> 00:39:53.550
big victory indeed.

00:39:56.700 --> 00:39:58.110
Yeah.

00:39:58.110 --> 00:40:02.460
Anyway, we start
with the 1961 plan

00:40:02.460 --> 00:40:05.190
for the University of Sussex.

00:40:05.190 --> 00:40:10.560
This is post-war,
post '45, rebuilding

00:40:10.560 --> 00:40:13.800
of educational
institutions in Europe.

00:40:13.800 --> 00:40:21.200
And I use this data just to make
an argument about the change.

00:40:21.200 --> 00:40:24.620
61 Sussex is a campus plan.

00:40:24.620 --> 00:40:26.900
They are separate schools.

00:40:26.900 --> 00:40:32.060
They are individual categories,
individual enterprises,

00:40:32.060 --> 00:40:38.040
School of Mathematics, School
of Humanities, and so on.

00:40:38.040 --> 00:40:42.480
By the University of
Lancaster in 1964,

00:40:42.480 --> 00:40:48.290
the tension starts being paid
to the connecting of places.

00:40:48.290 --> 00:40:52.880
And the system is one in
which modular space is

00:40:52.880 --> 00:40:56.915
connected in a complex network.

00:41:02.310 --> 00:41:07.230
Number four, the University of
East Anglia in 1961, the plan

00:41:07.230 --> 00:41:12.210
is now a solid
linear configuration

00:41:12.210 --> 00:41:16.680
with three small outgrowths.

00:41:16.680 --> 00:41:18.840
But the whole
system is very much

00:41:18.840 --> 00:41:21.585
based on the linearity of--

00:41:24.950 --> 00:41:29.180
number five, the University
of Essex in 1961,

00:41:29.180 --> 00:41:35.480
tries to take that linearity
and bend it up and down.

00:41:35.480 --> 00:41:38.240
By now, people are
asking questions

00:41:38.240 --> 00:41:43.400
of whether interdisciplinary
knowledge systems are not

00:41:43.400 --> 00:41:52.530
taking hold, biology and science
or physics and chemistry.

00:41:55.210 --> 00:41:59.190
So the breakdown of
conventional disciplines

00:41:59.190 --> 00:42:06.540
suggests the kind of grouping of
and even a future in which this

00:42:06.540 --> 00:42:13.950
might continue, allowing for
a switch to the next page,

00:42:13.950 --> 00:42:17.400
University of Surrey,
where you start

00:42:17.400 --> 00:42:23.884
getting some inclination of the
idea of building modular space

00:42:23.884 --> 00:42:27.180
of various dimensions.

00:42:27.180 --> 00:42:32.760
University of Dublin,
[? John Carver's ?] project

00:42:32.760 --> 00:42:37.110
starts trying to articulate
the linearity by having

00:42:37.110 --> 00:42:43.920
a central public spine, much
like the main corridor at MIT,

00:42:43.920 --> 00:42:49.350
and outgrowths from it
depending on the need

00:42:49.350 --> 00:42:56.100
to be close to the
public versus space which

00:42:56.100 --> 00:42:58.965
requires research privacy.

00:43:02.980 --> 00:43:09.230
We go down to the University
of Loughborough in 1965,

00:43:09.230 --> 00:43:13.930
which is a major,
major departure.

00:43:13.930 --> 00:43:19.750
Now, a 50 by 50
cube by 15 feet high

00:43:19.750 --> 00:43:22.180
is the only element
to be designed

00:43:22.180 --> 00:43:29.440
in the university space it will
account for 70% of the campus.

00:43:34.010 --> 00:43:35.540
What does this imply?

00:43:35.540 --> 00:43:39.840
It implies that we maximize
the possibility of change

00:43:39.840 --> 00:43:44.550
every space is endowed
with a service structure.

00:43:44.550 --> 00:43:52.400
So that my office can become a
space for a research scientist

00:43:52.400 --> 00:43:56.900
who needs specialized
heating, specialized air,

00:43:56.900 --> 00:44:02.390
specialized steam,
specialized power.

00:44:02.390 --> 00:44:07.230
If I produce all of
this for everybody,

00:44:07.230 --> 00:44:12.400
we can change with
maximum flexibility.

00:44:17.060 --> 00:44:19.490
Do you understand the idea?

00:44:19.490 --> 00:44:26.570
This is the ultimate measure
of flexibility, an item which

00:44:26.570 --> 00:44:32.070
has infinite flexibility.

00:44:32.070 --> 00:44:35.210
In a competition for the
university, new university

00:44:35.210 --> 00:44:37.790
of Bremen, one of
the competitors

00:44:37.790 --> 00:44:41.360
had a railway line right
through the middle of the campus

00:44:41.360 --> 00:44:44.540
with the train
with a crane on it.

00:44:44.540 --> 00:44:50.760
And it kept on moving the parts,
modules, all over the place.

00:44:50.760 --> 00:44:56.780
So if my department
grew, some modules

00:44:56.780 --> 00:45:00.570
could be added to the top
of our existing department.

00:45:00.570 --> 00:45:05.120
If we fired half of the
Department of Architecture,

00:45:05.120 --> 00:45:08.610
the modules could be replaced.

00:45:08.610 --> 00:45:12.590
If you speed that
up, you can imagine

00:45:12.590 --> 00:45:16.580
coming to your office on
Monday and needing an algorithm

00:45:16.580 --> 00:45:21.290
to explain where you should be
or where you're going to be.

00:45:23.970 --> 00:45:29.250
MIT's central corridor, despite
the changes, has remained.

00:45:29.250 --> 00:45:34.830
And it has a low rate of change.

00:45:34.830 --> 00:45:38.430
It should have changed
much more than it has,

00:45:38.430 --> 00:45:41.850
but it's become embedded
into the system,

00:45:41.850 --> 00:45:45.060
so that whilst almost every
other space at MIT has

00:45:45.060 --> 00:45:48.480
undergone change, it hasn't.

00:45:48.480 --> 00:45:53.250
It has the same old
dull administrative--

00:45:53.250 --> 00:45:56.860
instead of building a
cafeteria across the street,

00:45:56.860 --> 00:46:01.350
MIT should have jettisoned
its administrative facilities

00:46:01.350 --> 00:46:05.970
and used this major
corridor as a place

00:46:05.970 --> 00:46:10.260
for real public
exhibitions, for eating,

00:46:10.260 --> 00:46:12.930
for people coming together.

00:46:12.930 --> 00:46:13.455
It didn't.

00:46:17.000 --> 00:46:20.930
It lacked the
intelligence or the--

00:46:20.930 --> 00:46:24.500
but so excessive
flexibility is very costly.

00:46:27.360 --> 00:46:30.660
One of the reasons you
can't do advanced science

00:46:30.660 --> 00:46:35.070
in the old part of
MIT is because is

00:46:35.070 --> 00:46:36.870
the infrastructure is too weak.

00:46:40.630 --> 00:46:42.610
The sixth floor
of our building--

00:46:46.600 --> 00:46:51.400
our building has six floors.

00:46:51.400 --> 00:46:58.180
Well, the sixth
floor is for animals.

00:46:58.180 --> 00:47:04.120
All of animals are
generally in basement.

00:47:04.120 --> 00:47:09.760
One of the future for building
university research facilities

00:47:09.760 --> 00:47:13.780
given climate change--

00:47:13.780 --> 00:47:20.920
New York University, the animal
laboratories in the basement

00:47:20.920 --> 00:47:22.840
all flooded.

00:47:22.840 --> 00:47:26.200
All the research was lost.

00:47:26.200 --> 00:47:31.870
We put ours up in the
sky for no clear reasons.

00:47:31.870 --> 00:47:36.070
We thought the animals would be
better off in there than down

00:47:36.070 --> 00:47:37.420
in the basement.

00:47:37.420 --> 00:47:40.570
And nobody disagreed.

00:47:40.570 --> 00:47:46.000
On top of that floor is a floor
of machines, machines which

00:47:46.000 --> 00:47:48.700
look like airplane systems.

00:47:48.700 --> 00:47:58.960
Because the building is a
laboratory which has to account

00:47:58.960 --> 00:48:04.930
for research which requires
highly specialized vectors

00:48:04.930 --> 00:48:14.470
of steam, light, all kinds
of elements which the ceiling

00:48:14.470 --> 00:48:18.340
depths of about 18
inches, or 2 feet,

00:48:18.340 --> 00:48:23.200
in places is so dense that you
cannot get another pipe through

00:48:23.200 --> 00:48:23.700
there.

00:48:27.490 --> 00:48:32.020
If MIT would have allowed us to
account for future flexibility,

00:48:32.020 --> 00:48:36.820
we would have made the depth
greater than the 18 inches

00:48:36.820 --> 00:48:37.600
tube.

00:48:37.600 --> 00:48:41.100
It costs money.

00:48:41.100 --> 00:48:44.220
We weren't allowed
to plan the building

00:48:44.220 --> 00:48:50.245
with any space on the building
called TBA, To Be Added.

00:48:55.710 --> 00:48:59.700
It's like packing
an aircraft carrier.

00:48:59.700 --> 00:49:02.610
An aircraft carrier probably
can change internally.

00:49:02.610 --> 00:49:08.800
But anyway, let's move
on with these diagrams.

00:49:08.800 --> 00:49:10.860
We're got a few minutes left.

00:49:13.430 --> 00:49:19.250
The Potteries Thinkbelt
in 1966, was Cedric Price,

00:49:19.250 --> 00:49:24.020
the British architect's, attempt
to do a couple of things--

00:49:24.020 --> 00:49:26.480
to eliminate the
idea of a campus

00:49:26.480 --> 00:49:31.160
from having separateness
from the rest of urbanism.

00:49:34.350 --> 00:49:42.270
He decided to place
this British university

00:49:42.270 --> 00:49:48.830
in an area of suffering economic
decline in Staffordshire.

00:49:48.830 --> 00:49:55.970
He argued that this
embedding of the University

00:49:55.970 --> 00:50:01.130
into the society's needs
would spontaneously

00:50:01.130 --> 00:50:07.960
produce another kind
of university, such

00:50:07.960 --> 00:50:11.560
as it would stimulate the
economy, for instance,

00:50:11.560 --> 00:50:19.030
through promoting a
landlady industry and so on.

00:50:19.030 --> 00:50:23.460
Instead of building
university dormitories,

00:50:23.460 --> 00:50:40.130
I showed you a project in New
York by the Ford Foundation,

00:50:40.130 --> 00:50:45.620
which attempted to do the same
thing that, instead of building

00:50:45.620 --> 00:50:49.280
university dormitories,
create a market

00:50:49.280 --> 00:50:53.180
for the supply of housing
by the poor people

00:50:53.180 --> 00:50:54.710
around the university.

00:50:59.470 --> 00:51:03.370
The last of these plans is
the most famous of them.

00:51:03.370 --> 00:51:05.200
It's the Free
University in Berlin.

00:51:10.350 --> 00:51:19.996
Shadrach Woods writes
about this plan.

00:51:19.996 --> 00:51:22.240
"We have not begun
by trying to give

00:51:22.240 --> 00:51:24.820
fixed points within the system.

00:51:24.820 --> 00:51:26.980
I know they will have this.

00:51:26.980 --> 00:51:30.520
People make the identifiable
features, not the architect.

00:51:30.520 --> 00:51:33.670
I do not want to make any
symbols to begin with.

00:51:33.670 --> 00:51:35.410
I think that the
use of the building

00:51:35.410 --> 00:51:38.050
create centers of activity.

00:51:38.050 --> 00:51:40.730
The plan is really an
attempt not to make sense--"

00:51:40.730 --> 00:51:41.950
and so on to begin with.

00:51:44.840 --> 00:51:50.700
It's interesting
that the implication

00:51:50.700 --> 00:51:57.240
is that, if you give an
opportunity for people

00:51:57.240 --> 00:52:00.840
to arrange themselves,
they will have the capacity

00:52:00.840 --> 00:52:05.010
to do so in a correct
manner or in a manner that

00:52:05.010 --> 00:52:07.920
is correct for them.

00:52:07.920 --> 00:52:13.110
This is a time when Noam
Chomsky was lecturing

00:52:13.110 --> 00:52:17.700
about the innate
ability of a child

00:52:17.700 --> 00:52:21.030
to construct a specific
system of interconnection

00:52:21.030 --> 00:52:25.740
amongst concepts and
conditions of use and reference

00:52:25.740 --> 00:52:29.370
on the basis of scanty
and scattered evidence.

00:52:32.470 --> 00:52:37.960
Is there DNA in human
beings which automatically

00:52:37.960 --> 00:52:44.590
will be able to create better
space than a specialist guiding

00:52:44.590 --> 00:52:45.220
them?

00:52:45.220 --> 00:52:49.210
Or what combination of the two?

00:52:49.210 --> 00:52:52.353
Classical anarchism is--

00:52:52.353 --> 00:52:53.770
AUDIENCE: That
would be the wisdom

00:52:53.770 --> 00:52:57.122
of the crowd in that sense.

00:52:57.122 --> 00:52:58.580
JULIAN BEINART:
Well, as I can only

00:52:58.580 --> 00:53:04.760
judge from Shadrach Woods,
who was a very good architect,

00:53:04.760 --> 00:53:07.220
this is absolutely
anti-classical.

00:53:09.840 --> 00:53:15.330
The crowd will organize itself
as it goes along and works

00:53:15.330 --> 00:53:17.640
and studies.

00:53:17.640 --> 00:53:22.230
There will be a
generation of space

00:53:22.230 --> 00:53:27.330
which will be more the result of
the participation of the people

00:53:27.330 --> 00:53:28.830
than imposed on them.

00:53:28.830 --> 00:53:32.250
I'm putting it rather
crudely, the notion that there

00:53:32.250 --> 00:53:38.430
is a DNA in all human beings,
according to Chomsky, which

00:53:38.430 --> 00:53:44.610
allows a child to
construct complex sentences

00:53:44.610 --> 00:53:48.720
without having been
told how to do it,

00:53:48.720 --> 00:53:52.140
admittedly with the parents
and society around them

00:53:52.140 --> 00:53:55.920
to guide them.

00:53:55.920 --> 00:53:59.726
But Chomsky is fairly
well-established

00:53:59.726 --> 00:54:02.550
as an authority now.

00:54:02.550 --> 00:54:07.170
There's still controversy
around whether the DNA of people

00:54:07.170 --> 00:54:09.795
have this capacity
without much learning.

00:54:14.770 --> 00:54:17.170
My own position about--

00:54:17.170 --> 00:54:20.830
the Free University
has had a bad history.

00:54:20.830 --> 00:54:22.180
It's been vandalized.

00:54:22.180 --> 00:54:23.910
It's been destroyed.

00:54:23.910 --> 00:54:30.400
It's had to be rebuilt. It
never fulfilled the promise

00:54:30.400 --> 00:54:34.420
that Woods had for it.

00:54:34.420 --> 00:54:37.870
So what we see through
all of these cases,

00:54:37.870 --> 00:54:45.010
from Sussex in '61 where the
armature of separated items

00:54:45.010 --> 00:54:54.460
in a campus are dismantled
into a system, which

00:54:54.460 --> 00:55:02.680
is almost cybernetic in a sense,
free associations of networks

00:55:02.680 --> 00:55:07.510
created freely over time
suggesting new relationships.

00:55:11.390 --> 00:55:14.265
The trouble with architecture
is that it's not easy.

00:55:17.930 --> 00:55:22.460
You just can't take a piece of
paper and stick it on a wall.

00:55:22.460 --> 00:55:26.330
The wall has to have bearing.

00:55:26.330 --> 00:55:29.270
Acoustics unfortunately
means that the only way

00:55:29.270 --> 00:55:31.955
to separate sound is with mass.

00:55:35.920 --> 00:55:38.250
The university is the
last place in the world

00:55:38.250 --> 00:55:44.580
to flitter around with stud
walls or prefabricated metal

00:55:44.580 --> 00:55:46.410
panels.

00:55:46.410 --> 00:55:51.600
If we had a prefabricated
metal panel uninsulated,

00:55:51.600 --> 00:55:53.880
we wouldn't be able to
teach in this class.

00:55:56.530 --> 00:56:00.570
So again, the
Poisson distribution

00:56:00.570 --> 00:56:05.340
might guide one into knowing
the frequency of places which

00:56:05.340 --> 00:56:09.130
need acoustic separation
versus those that

00:56:09.130 --> 00:56:13.230
don't in the same way that
the Loughborough possibility

00:56:13.230 --> 00:56:16.430
of making everything possible--

00:56:16.430 --> 00:56:19.500
a Poisson distribution would
say that the likelihood

00:56:19.500 --> 00:56:24.870
of wet laboratories occurring
in your campus are this.

00:56:24.870 --> 00:56:28.080
And, therefore, you should
only spend the money

00:56:28.080 --> 00:56:35.520
on a feasible solution, which
requires 70% of your buildings

00:56:35.520 --> 00:56:37.890
to have this flexibility.

00:56:37.890 --> 00:56:42.930
The Stata building has no
wet laboratories in it.

00:56:42.930 --> 00:56:46.140
Therefore, it has nothing--

00:56:46.140 --> 00:56:48.330
I mean, if you knew
architecture well enough,

00:56:48.330 --> 00:56:51.150
you could look at the Stata
building and our building

00:56:51.150 --> 00:56:53.910
and compare them
fundamentally and say,

00:56:53.910 --> 00:56:56.040
the one has wet
laboratories, the one

00:56:56.040 --> 00:57:00.660
doesn't have any, by looking
at the amount of chimneys

00:57:00.660 --> 00:57:03.280
on the roof.

00:57:03.280 --> 00:57:10.690
We have every kind of chimney
emanating smoke or gas,

00:57:10.690 --> 00:57:12.970
whatever comes from MIT.

00:57:15.960 --> 00:57:18.630
The Stata building has nothing.

00:57:18.630 --> 00:57:20.940
There's a flat ceiling roof.

00:57:20.940 --> 00:57:25.170
It's the only flat
plane in the building.

00:57:25.170 --> 00:57:27.100
OK.

00:57:27.100 --> 00:57:35.580
I want to look briefly
at two other cases.

00:57:35.580 --> 00:57:37.725
The one is the--

00:57:37.725 --> 00:57:44.880
by the way, there's a
piece by William Fawcett

00:57:44.880 --> 00:57:51.810
in the MIT Planning Journal,
one or two volumes ago,

00:57:51.810 --> 00:57:56.940
on flexible life, flexibility.

00:57:56.940 --> 00:58:01.650
It's called "Investment in
Flexibility, the Life Cycle

00:58:01.650 --> 00:58:05.700
Options Synthesis."

00:58:05.700 --> 00:58:10.620
He gives examples
of prediction which

00:58:10.620 --> 00:58:14.610
is based on estimates of
outcome and the costing

00:58:14.610 --> 00:58:17.430
of the estimates of outcome
and the decision which

00:58:17.430 --> 00:58:20.810
is based on the system.

00:58:23.460 --> 00:58:27.930
I'd also recommend that you read
something in Kevin Lynch's book

00:58:27.930 --> 00:58:30.990
What Time Is This Place?

00:58:30.990 --> 00:58:35.430
for an attempt, in the
space-time continuum,

00:58:35.430 --> 00:58:38.930
to play around with
the idea of time.

00:58:38.930 --> 00:58:41.610
There's a page in which he
goes through a whole number

00:58:41.610 --> 00:58:46.080
of possibilities
of changing time.

00:58:46.080 --> 00:58:50.820
And he doesn't speculate about
his implications on space.

00:58:55.990 --> 00:58:59.680
I'm going to skip a bunch of
stuff and end with the last two

00:58:59.680 --> 00:59:01.120
because we won't have time.

00:59:05.287 --> 00:59:09.290
I'll deal with this
mainly through the slides.

00:59:12.910 --> 00:59:16.360
I can't find the right place.

00:59:16.360 --> 00:59:23.950
The two cases are the use
of temporary environment

00:59:23.950 --> 00:59:26.860
of a fairly large
scale in cities.

00:59:26.860 --> 00:59:37.120
The one is the story of
Paris between 1855 and 1900.

00:59:37.120 --> 00:59:39.520
After the success of
the Crystal Palace

00:59:39.520 --> 00:59:43.510
Exhibition in 1851
in London, the French

00:59:43.510 --> 00:59:47.215
built an exhibition in 1855.

00:59:47.215 --> 00:59:57.220
And almost every 11 years
afterwards, 1855, 1867, 1878,

00:59:57.220 --> 01:00:03.400
1889, and 1900, it
had an exhibition,

01:00:03.400 --> 01:00:06.880
a temporary exhibition, a
major temporary exhibition

01:00:06.880 --> 01:00:10.780
in the center of Paris
just north of the Seine

01:00:10.780 --> 01:00:12.563
and largely south of the Seine.

01:00:16.922 --> 01:00:20.630
I'll go through some of the
material with the slides,

01:00:20.630 --> 01:00:31.370
but let me read you a quote
from the French novelist

01:00:31.370 --> 01:00:36.230
Jean Giraudoux
about the existence

01:00:36.230 --> 01:00:40.220
of a temporary
city in conjunction

01:00:40.220 --> 01:00:43.570
with a permanent city.

01:00:43.570 --> 01:00:45.970
He's talking about
the citizens of Paris.

01:00:45.970 --> 01:00:47.830
"They are delighted
by the thought

01:00:47.830 --> 01:00:50.470
of reaching this
cardboard or plaster

01:00:50.470 --> 01:00:55.790
city, which is a permanent
stone site of Paris."

01:00:55.790 --> 01:01:02.325
What an extraordinary idea,
that part of your city

01:01:02.325 --> 01:01:06.740
is rotating at a faster
speed than the other parts.

01:01:10.380 --> 01:01:14.280
The Free University of
Berlin has no stone site.

01:01:14.280 --> 01:01:17.670
It only has transparency.

01:01:17.670 --> 01:01:22.590
Maybe you need a balance between
stone site and cardboard.

01:01:26.470 --> 01:01:27.370
He goes on.

01:01:30.080 --> 01:01:35.020
"They do not come to see it
disguised and transvestized

01:01:35.020 --> 01:01:35.520
Paris."

01:01:39.770 --> 01:01:44.230
The exhibitions are
not transvestized

01:01:44.230 --> 01:01:48.140
Paris, not changed Paris.

01:01:48.140 --> 01:01:49.250
But they are unique.

01:01:49.250 --> 01:01:51.110
They are on their own.

01:01:51.110 --> 01:01:54.980
"They come attracted
by the temporary union

01:01:54.980 --> 01:02:00.560
of an ephemeral city with a
millennial one, the association

01:02:00.560 --> 01:02:02.780
of the most eccentric
city with the most

01:02:02.780 --> 01:02:04.970
real and tangible one."

01:02:04.970 --> 01:02:07.340
It's an extraordinary
idea that you

01:02:07.340 --> 01:02:13.325
keep the center of your city
to change at a more rapid rate.

01:02:13.325 --> 01:02:23.780
I'll show you slides of 1867
being the first structure

01:02:23.780 --> 01:02:25.400
and the demolition.

01:02:25.400 --> 01:02:28.650
That takes place within
a period of 11 years.

01:02:28.650 --> 01:02:33.470
So every child in the city
is seeing construction

01:02:33.470 --> 01:02:40.260
and destruction until 1900.

01:02:40.260 --> 01:02:46.040
Of course, the most significant
event takes place in 1889

01:02:46.040 --> 01:02:53.630
and considered a
temporary phenomenon.

01:02:53.630 --> 01:02:55.880
The Eiffel Tower is
the most permanent

01:02:55.880 --> 01:02:58.940
of all phenomena in Paris.

01:02:58.940 --> 01:03:04.940
So again, out of this
temporary sea of change,

01:03:04.940 --> 01:03:10.100
there are a couple of
items which remain and log

01:03:10.100 --> 01:03:13.280
into a system of permanence.

01:03:13.280 --> 01:03:15.920
Although the Eiffel
Tower was regarded

01:03:15.920 --> 01:03:22.190
as an American structure, easily
taken apart and assembled,

01:03:22.190 --> 01:03:27.740
a fabricated structure unlike
the solid neoclassical form

01:03:27.740 --> 01:03:31.220
of a Parisian facade.

01:03:31.220 --> 01:03:35.420
The TrocadÃ©ro, which was on
the other side of the Seine

01:03:35.420 --> 01:03:37.220
in the 1878--

01:03:37.220 --> 01:03:41.450
the 1889 exhibition,
was demolished.

01:03:41.450 --> 01:03:46.670
Although it had a plaster
facade and looked as

01:03:46.670 --> 01:03:49.320
if it had been there forever.

01:03:49.320 --> 01:03:54.740
So these juxtapositions are
interesting in themselves.

01:03:54.740 --> 01:04:00.590
The last and the most permanent
of temporary phenomena

01:04:00.590 --> 01:04:01.700
are the Olympic Games.

01:04:04.980 --> 01:04:14.280
In 1896, the Olympic
Games was an attempt

01:04:14.280 --> 01:04:24.000
to recapitulate one of
Greece's ongoing traditions.

01:04:24.000 --> 01:04:30.240
That is the ancient site
of Olympia 776 BC, which

01:04:30.240 --> 01:04:35.280
consisted of two components, a
permanent religious component

01:04:35.280 --> 01:04:41.850
with priests dealing with flames
and an outdoor camp series

01:04:41.850 --> 01:04:49.140
of components, gymnasia,
stadia, palestra, health spa,

01:04:49.140 --> 01:04:55.290
and so on dealing with
a cultural attribute

01:04:55.290 --> 01:05:01.320
of the body being performed in
competition every four years.

01:05:01.320 --> 01:05:10.140
In 1896, [INAUDIBLE] decided
to make some mileage out

01:05:10.140 --> 01:05:14.520
of reclaiming this idea.

01:05:14.520 --> 01:05:18.510
1900, the Olympic Games
were held in Paris

01:05:18.510 --> 01:05:23.420
at the time of the
1900 Exposition.

01:05:23.420 --> 01:05:25.050
The Olympic Games was nothing.

01:05:25.050 --> 01:05:26.565
It was a joke.

01:05:26.565 --> 01:05:29.400
